leadership-approach|people_vision_results_process|concentrated|people|vision|results|process|How People organises the response|People is likely to organise the first response by checking trust, communication, inclusion, and what people need in order to move with the work. Vision and Results add useful checks, while Process may need deliberate attention before the response becomes too narrow.|This shows up when pressure makes trust, shared understanding, and commitment feel like the clearest way to begin. The next signals test whether the work also has a wider direction and a reason for the choice being made, a clear outcome and a decision people can act on, and usable structure and a sequence people can trust.|It protects the work from low trust, weak buy-in, poor communication, and people being left behind by the pace of work. The main range to add is clearer steps, standards, and handover, especially when the first response has already created movement.|active|leadership-approach::people_vision_results_process::concentrated
leadership-approach|people_vision_results_process|paired|people|vision|results|process|How People and Vision work together|People and Vision tend to operate as a close working pair. People gives the first entry point, while Vision quickly changes how the response is explained, organised, or carried into action.|This shows up when the situation seems to need both communication, confidence, and shared commitment and a wider direction and a reason for the choice being made. Results can steady the pair, and Process is the range to bring in before the pair becomes too narrow.|It protects the link between trust and shared commitment and direction and future consequence. It also needs enough room for clearer steps, standards, and handover when the top pair starts to take most of the attention.|active|leadership-approach::people_vision_results_process::paired
leadership-approach|people_vision_results_process|graduated|people|vision|results|process|How the pattern moves from People to Process|The pattern tends to move in steps: People starts the response, Vision gives the next influence, Results adds support, and Process may need to be brought in deliberately.|This shows up when leadership attention follows a clear order rather than moving evenly between several options. Each step adds a different check on what the work now needs.|It protects a coherent sequence from trust and shared commitment towards outcome and follow-through. The main watch point is leaving clearer steps, standards, and handover until the work has already narrowed.|active|leadership-approach::people_vision_results_process::graduated
leadership-approach|people_vision_results_process|balanced|people|vision|results|process|How the pattern moves between People, Vision, Results, and Process|The pattern may have several usable entry points. People may appear first, but context can quickly call for Vision, Results, or Process without making the response inconsistent.|This shows up when the situation contains several kinds of leadership demand at once. The useful skill is naming which need is current rather than moving between them silently.|It protects flexibility across trust and shared commitment, direction and future consequence, outcome and follow-through, and structure and standards. It needs a clear current priority so others can follow the shift.|active|leadership-approach::people_vision_results_process::balanced
leadership-approach|people_vision_process_results|concentrated|people|vision|process|results|How People organises the response|People is likely to organise the first response by checking trust, communication, inclusion, and what people need in order to move with the work. Vision and Process add useful checks, while Results may need deliberate attention before the response becomes too narrow.|This shows up when pressure makes trust, shared understanding, and commitment feel like the clearest way to begin. The next signals test whether the work also has a wider direction and a reason for the choice being made, usable structure and a sequence people can trust, and a clear outcome and a decision people can act on.|It protects the work from low trust, weak buy-in, poor communication, and people being left behind by the pace of work. The main range to add is firmer outcome, ownership, and follow-through, especially when the first response has already created movement.|active|leadership-approach::people_vision_process_results::concentrated
